##Gucci and other luxury goods cut supplier orders, you buy the bag will be delayed

On 12 March, Italy suspended all non-essential business activities throughout the country, except for grocery and drug stores, in an effort to prevent the spread of the disease. The next day Gucci, the Italian luxury brand, decided to temporarily close all its factories in Italy until March 20.

Gucci has six manufacturing bases in Italy, in the Tuscany and Marche regions.

A Gucci spokesman said the temporary closure of the factory would not affect the supply of products and the brand's global website continued to operate, Women's Wear Daily reported. "The brand will continue to operate as necessary to ensure continuity of current and future business operations. "

The spokesman added that Gucci has asked all staff in its Italian offices to work flexibly and flexibly in a variety of ways, such as working only four days a week.

Flavio Cereda, an analyst at Wall Street Investment Bank Jefferies & Company, has predicted that long term disruptions in economic activity are likely to cause supply chain problems for most brands. This phenomenon will be seen more quickly in areas with severe outbreaks.

Luxury brands, including Gucci and Louis Vuitton, have cut back on orders for Italian suppliers as Italy has become the eye of the epidemic, Reuters reported on March 9.

Local textile and leather suppliers told Reuters that orders had actually fallen sharply when the outbreak broke out in China in late January.

"We make 800-1,000 bags a month for Gucci. We made 450 in February and had no orders in March, " said the boss of a small supplier, whose parent company, the Kering Group, is one of the supplier's main customers. He also said orders for April and May were nowhere to be found and had to be made temporarily redundant.

Scandinavian-based producer Almax makes handbags for 10 brands, including Kering's Saint Laurent, Gucci and Balenciaga, as well as some of LVMH's brands. Massimiliano Guerrini, the manufacturer's owner, said orders had fallen several percent during the previous outbreak in China.

"What's going on in Italy right now could kill more businesses than humans, " Guerrini said.

Italian luxury brand FERRAGAMO has told its staff to implement a four-day week for the next two months and to stop hiring new staff and renew fixed-term contracts, Reuters reported, citing a person familiar with the matter. Giorgio Armani closed his factory in northern Italy for a week in late February after a closed-door show.

As of 8:00 on March 13,2,651 new cases had been confirmed in Italy, bringing the total to 15,113 with 1,016 deaths. The wife of Canadian Prime Minister Trudo was also diagnosed on the 13th, and Trudo began to isolate herself.

The local fashion industry is also nervous, the capital market first lost confidence, leading to the Italian luxury group shares fell collectively.

Tod's shares were down 11.1 per cent at one point, Salvatore Ferragamo down 9.2 per cent, Safilo down 8.2 per cent and Moncler down at most 5.8 per cent.

Chiara Ferragni, an Italian who is one of the world's most popular fashion bloggers, has repeatedly called on social media in the past two days to alert her fans to the dangers of the outbreak. She noted that there were many cases in Italy and many people did not have access to effective care, and hospitals were not prepared to deal with the worsening situation. To that end, she has launched a crowdfunding campaign to help a hospital in Milan.

Claudio Marenzi, CEO of Confindustria Moda, an Italian fashion association with more than 65,000 brand members, told Women's Wear Daily that he was studying how associations and brands could help each other in the textile and fashion supply chain, but it is hard to make any predictions about its effectiveness or impact.

In addition to the supply chain side, many luxury brands in Europe have been forced by the epidemic to change their offline activities in the first half of the year.

Gucci, for example, canceled the launch of its 2021 vacation series, which was scheduled for May 18 in San Francisco. Burberry, which had planned to host a 2020 autumn / Winter Revival show in Shanghai at the end of April, has also announced a delay. Prada has postponed a holiday show scheduled for May 21 in Japan. Arrangements for brands such as Chanel, Dior and Max Mara have also changed.

While Ōhide is one of the most important offline activities for any brand, it's easy to run the risk of spreading the virus in large crowds.

Gucci recently learned that two people who attended the fall / Winter 2020 series on February 19 were diagnosed with new coronary pneumonia. While there is no evidence that they were infected at the Gucci Show, the brand quickly contacted other attendees and informed them of the significance of the incident.

Gucci has told interface fashion: "In this special period, Gucci will always be concerned about the people and areas affected by the epidemic, and strictly follow the government's anti-epidemic measures to ensure the health of employees and guests. "

It will be a constant battle for all European luxury brands. Global luxury goods companies will lose at least $10bn in profits by 2020, according to a new report by Altagamma, an Italian luxury goods association, BCG, a consultancy, and Bernstein, an asset management firm. The majority of those surveyed expect the global luxury market to be negatively affected by the outbreak over the next three months to six months.
